      <avSnowComment>&lt;p&gt;Over the past 24 hours 13 to 18 inches of snow fell across the Southern San Juan zone with light to moderate southwesterly winds. Coal Bank Pass and Wolf Creek Pass received 18 inches and 13 inches reported at Durango Mountain Resort. Southwest winds have been strong enough to move the new snow into new drifts. The weight of the storm snow, with around an inch of water, is enough to stress our weak snowpack and the wind will push it to the breaking point. An avalanche could break into buried layers of weak snow, producing large and dangerous slides. In the western portion of the zone, which encompasses the La Plata Mountains, Needle Mountains and the Grenadier Range there are areas of HIGH (Level 4) avalanche danger where recent storm slabs and wind slabs sit on persistent weak layers. Natural avalanches are likely and human-triggered avalanches are very likely today.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Although buried weak layers remain an issue across the zone, the snowpack is generally stronger on the eastside of the zone.&amp;nbsp; Avalanches in the storm snow layer and below fresh wind slabs are presenting the greatest danger in this area. There are also multiple layers of buried surface hoar, 3 to 5 feet down, near Wolf Creek Pass. If you trigger an avalanche in the storm snow, it could be large enough to break down to one of these surface hoar layers. Look for the surface hoar on sheltered slopes that face northwest through north and to the east.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Today is a good day to avoid traveling on or below avalanche terrain.&lt;/p&gt;</avSnowComment>
